The Supreme Court’s current term may have started with a whimper, but it will end with a bang.
In recent weeks, the justices added three cases related to electoral power and influence in the United States.
Taken together, the rulings could have a dramatic effect on the shape and quality of American democracy for the next decade.
Last week, the court announced it would hear Department of Commerce v. New York, the dispute over Trump’s proposed citizenship question.
State legislators use it to redraw their own legislative maps.